<span style="font-weight: 400;">¬†</span><b>Natural and lifestyle treatment of ulcerative colitis</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Some natural treatment of the disease includes:</span>

<b>Food</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Some foods and drinks can cause the symptoms especially at the stage of flare up. However since studies discovered its prevalence to the Western race, the condition is likely to be caused by processed foods ( which is more prevalent in that part of the world).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Some foods that may cause ulcers include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Excessive fiber such as fruits, nuts, vegetables and whole grain.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Dairy and gluten as they tend to disrupt the smooth process of digestion.</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">¬†</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Beverages and foods that irritate the lining of the digestive canal.</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Method of reducing ulcerative colitis</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">A strong relationship exists between the gut and mind. It's important to learn how to reduce stress in order to combat ulcer. You can reduce stress by doing the following:</span>

<b>Regular exercise: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">This activity helps to manage ulcerative colitis symptoms and complications. Cool and calm exercises such as yoga relax the digestive system and heal the body and mind.</span>

<b>Meditation: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Meditative exercise includes taking a deep breath and relaxing the muscles.</span>

<b>Work with a therapist: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">A cognitive behavioral therapist can help with symptoms of an ulcer. You'll be helped to cope with pain and stress of flare up. They can also help with muscle relaxation techniques.</span>

